##Please note that we now recommend campers use their Campsite’s Facebook group for chatting instead of their campsite’s Gitter chatroom. 
We are doing this because few of our Campsite Gitter chatroooms have active synchronous discussions, and about 1/3rd of conversations consist of someone saying “hello” and not getting a response. Most of the discussions are asynchronous, which Facebook posts and group messages are better suited for.
We’ve removed this Gitter room from our Campsite directory. Still, we will keep it open for archival purposes, and you can keep using it if you’d like.
Here’s a short blog post about how our Campsites are evolving and growing: http://blog.freecodecamp.com/2015/09/jump-start-your-local-campsite-with-coffee-and-code.html

@anjanjanj Im not really sure whats out there. I know there is alot, I just don't really know what it means to be any of the various IT professions. I first started with python and made a simple pygame game. I found this really stimulating, doing the research and seeing this thing come to fruition. That I felt if I could get a profession that made me feel like this, I would be content. Something that challenged me intellectually, where there would be some kind of problem and I would be assigned to find a solution to it.
What I also like about this industry, is I can work for anywhere, from anywhere in the world, a truly global industry.
I know my answer is extremely vague, I just don't want to pigeon hole myself yet.
I have a feeling I want to go more towards back-end, but at the same time not entirely sure what that means. All I know is I want my head stuck in code.

I have studied enough java to sit my programmer 1 exam. https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/extra/certification/javase-7-programmer1.html
I just need to book it in.

When I look on job sites in Australia I see heaps of positions for junior java developers. And even more in England and America. If I could get one of these I would be stocked, right now I just want something that will give me exposure to the industry.
